Since bilinear combinations $RL$ cannot be SU(3) singlets, the leading superfluid (SF)
instability corresponds to condensation of six-quark bound states. 
It corresponds to a singularity in the response function of  the deuteron operator (\ref{delta0}). Its amplitude  Tr$(G+G^+)$ acquires a vacuum expectation value only at $K < K_c$ and the operator simplifies: $\Delta \sim \exp({i}\sqrt{6\pi}\theta)$ so that
its scaling dimension is $d_{\Delta} = 3\tilde K/2,$ yielding a singular susceptibility for $\tilde K \leq 2/3$. 
In the baryon metal phase existing for  $K >K_c$, $G$-matrix field remains critical with $d=3/10$ and $
d_{\Delta} = 3(\tilde K/2+1/10)$,  
which yields a singular susceptibility at $\tilde K \leq 7/15$. Since the $I=1$ six-quark bound state has the same scaling dimension as $I=0$ one, the isospin $I = 1$ bosons can also have a singular susceptibility in the baryon metal phase.



Another order parameter is the $2k_F$ DW one related to the scalar meson operator  $
\Delta_{DW}= R^+_{a\alpha}L_{a\alpha} \sim {\mbox{e}}^{-{i}\sqrt{2\pi/3}\phi}\mbox{Tr}G.$
Once the isospin sector is gapped ${\langle} \mbox{Tr} G{\rangle} \neq 0$ and the scaling dimension of this order parameter is 
$
d_{DW} = 1/6\tilde K.
$
Hence at $1/6 <\tilde K < 2/3$ both the DW and superfluid susceptibilities are singular. In a quasi-1D system these order parameters compete and which one wins depends on factors outside of the 1D model. 

{\bf Conclusions}. Our results demonstrate  that (1+1)-D  
NJL model reproduces many  properties expected for its (1+3)-D prototype \cite{witten}. In particular, it has stable  fermionic solitons with quantum numbers of baryons:  U(1) charge $\pm 1$, SU(2) isospin $I=1/2$ (nucleons) and $I=3/2$ ($\Delta$-baryons). There are also  stable excitations with quantum numbers of mesons (U(1) neutral  particles with isospin 0 and 1 and Lorentz spin 0), and six-quark bound states (dibaryons and deuterons). 


