\subsection{Dibaryons}

The spectrum of the truncated conformal space only involves sectors of even 
baryonic charge due to the periodic boundary conditions on the conformal 
fields. In the sector with baryon charge $2$ we find both isospin singlet 
and triplet bound states, as shown by the spectrum in Fig. \ref{fig:dibaryons}. 
The isospin singlet state (coming in two copies due to the doubly degenerate 
vacuum) is the analogue of the deuteron. However, the isotriplet has 
no analogue in 3+1 dimensional strong interactions; the
reason is that in the isospin triplet channel the nucleon-nucleon potential 
is not attractive enough to form a bound state. However in one-dimensional
space any attractive potential -- no matter how shallow -- leads to a bound
state. Form these considerations the appearance of the isotriplet bound state 
(two of which would correspond to proton-proton and neutron-neutron bound state
in usual strong interaction terms) is not so surprising.

For higher values of $K$ one of the triplets joins the continuum, 
i.e. the corresponding bound state disappears. For small $K$, one expects 
that the dynamics of isosinglet states is dominated by the sine-Gordon like 
dynamics of the field $\phi$, as the isospin degrees of freedom corresponding 
to the WZNW field $G$ are frozen. The isosinglet dibaryon excitations 
correspond to sine-Gordon solitons, while the isosinglet mesons to the breathers. 
